observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct:
a. Instruct the General Services Office- Designate and the Inventory Committee to conduct inventory of all PPEs and prepare the Report of the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) by Section 156 of COA Circular No. 92-386; (Reiterated in CY 2024 AAR Observation No. 1)
b. Direct the responsible officers to comply with the disposition procedures for non-existing/missing properties, in compliance with Item 7.0 of COA Circular No. 2020-006;
c. Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
c.1. Strictly follow the recording of a tangible item as PPE, if and only if, it meets the definition and recognition criteria for PPE, which includes the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00, following Item No. 4.2 of COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022;
c.2. Reclassify tangible items with acquisition cost of less than ₱50,000.00 initially classified as Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE) to semi-expendable properties in accordance with Item No. 4.1 of Commission on Audit (COA) Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022;
c.3. Reflect the correct Depreciation Expense and Accumulated Depreciation of the PPE in accordance with Paragraph 71 of International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSAS) 17;
c.4. Draw journal entries to transfer the School Buildings amounting to ₱4.099 million from the Trust Fund to the General Fund, in compliance with Section 104 (1) of the MNGAS for LGUs;
c.5. Correct the erroneous recording of PPE, semi-expendable property and financial assistance;
c.6. Facilitate the reconciliation of the PPE Balance between the PPE Ledger Cards and the Financial Statements; and
c.7. Make the necessary adjustments in derecognizing the non-existing/missing assets in the books after the conduct of the physical inventory and after the disposition procedures for the said non-existing/missing assets were carried out.
d. Direct the GSO to prepare the Property Cards and reconcile the same with the Accounting records, following Section 119, Chapter 7 of the Manual on the New Government Accounting System (MNGAS) Manual;
e. Provide additional manpower, when feasible, to assist in the preparation and reconciliation of PPE records and reports;
f. Require the Inventory Committee, in compliance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to:
f.1. Prioritize the preparation of the approved PIP and submit it to the Office of the Auditor, at least 10 calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory-taking activities; and
f.2 Conduct the one-time cleansing of the PPE to establish the correct value of the account.

We recommended and the Management agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
a. Expedite the retrieval of the supporting documents of the outstanding cash advances and the reconciliation of the accounts with the supporting documents;
b. Identify the accountable officers with unliquidated cash advances and prepare the Subsidiary Ledgers and the detailed aging schedule of the account;
c. Demand immediate liquidation of the ₱1.567 million from the Accountable Officers with outstanding cash advances;
d. Withhold the AO's salary when no liquidation of the previous cash advance is received on or before January 20 of the ensuing year, in compliance with Section 5.9 of COA Circular No. 97-002;
e. Enforce strict compliance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 and Section 89 pf P.D. No. 1445 on the grant and liquidation of cash advances; and
f. Conduct regular and periodic verification, analysis and validation of cash advances to determine long outstanding and dormant receivables and prepare necessary reports together with the supporting documents for possible request for write-off, if warranted, as indicated in COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the Municipal Assessor’s Office to:
a. Expedite the titling of all parcels of land owned by the Municipal Government in compliance with Section 148 of COA Circular No. 92-386 and furnish the Municipal Accountant of the supporting documents for recording purposes;
b. Create an Appraisal Committee, headed by the Municipal Assessor and with representatives from each department concerned, to conduct the appraisal of the land claimed as owned by the Municipality to be used as basis for recording of the Land account balance;
c. The Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory of all the parcels of land owned by the Municipality consistent with Section 5.1 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 and reconcile with the records in the books; and
d. The Municipal Accountant to record in the books the land owned by the Municipality upon the receipt of the land titles, following Section 72 of the Manual on the New Government Accounting System (MNGAS) for Local Government Units (LGUs).

1.6 We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to direct:
a. The Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of the Municipality’s PPE and prepare and submit the RPCPPE under COA Circular No. 2020-006;
b. The GSO Designate to update and maintain Property Cards and to reconcile balances thereof with that of the accounting records regularly pursuant to Sections 119 and 120 of NGAS Manual for LGUs;
c. Municipal Accountant and the GSO Designate to conduct periodic reconciliation of the accounting and property records with the physical count and make the necessary adjustments on any discrepancies noted for an accurate and fair presentation of PPE account balances in the financial statements;
d. Concerned officials should take appropriate actions and expedite land registration in the Municipality's name.

2.9 We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:
a. Municipal Accountant to:
1.) Exert efforts in order to locate the necessary documents supporting the unreconciled beginning balance so that proper adjustments could be effected in the books;
2.) Review and make necessary adjustments to subsidiary ledgers with negative balances;
3.) Reclassify all completed projects from the CIP account to appropriate asset accounts and take up the corresponding depreciation expenses of the completed projects from the time these were completed; and
b. Municipal Engineer to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant after project validation/ inspection and periodically reconcile project status with the accounting records so that the proper adjustments may be made to the CIP accounts.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
Ensure that the members of the Inventory Committee are made aware of their designations for them to effectively carry out their respective duties and responsibilities;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer to facilitate the preparation of the Property Plant and Equipment (PPE) Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, and reconcile the same, in accordance with Sections 119 and 120, Chapter 7 of the New Government Accounting System (NGAS) Manual;
Provide additional manpower, when feasible, to assist in the preparation and reconciliation of PPE records and reports;
Instruct the GSO and the Inventory Committee to conduct inventory of all PPEs and prepare the Report of the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) in accordance with Section 156 of COA Circular No. 92-386;
Direct the responsible officers to comply with the disposition procedures for non-existing/missing properties, in compliance with Item 7.0 of COA Circular 
No. 2020-006;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Make the necessary adjustments to restate the PPE balance following the capitalization threshold for PPE of ₱50,000.00, in accordance with Item 4.2 of COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022;
Strictly follow the recording of a tangible item as PPE, if and only if, it meets the definition and recognition criteria for PPE, which includes the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00; and
Make the necessary adjustments in derecognizing the non-existing/missing assets in the books after the conduct of the physical inventory and after the disposition procedures for the said non-existing/missing assets were carried out.
Require the Inventory Committee, in compliance with COA Circular 
No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to:
Prioritize the preparation of the approved Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) and submit it to the Office of the Auditor, at least 10 calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory-taking activities; and
Conduct the one-time cleansing of the PPE to establish the correct value of the account.

We recommended and the management agreed that the Municipal Accountant to request a copy of the missing bank statements from the authorized bank in order to itemize the reconciling item in the amount of ₱0.692 million to determine their nature and make necessary adjusting entries, if necessary;
We also recommended that the OIC - Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant in the adjustment of the identified reconciling items and provide the latter the needed data especially on the stale checks returned by the payees; and
Instruct the offices concerned to communicate to all the payees with long outstanding checks regarding the status of the checks issued and immediately take necessary action after the payee has returned the stale check to the Municipality.

We recommended and the management agreed for the following:
The OIC- Municipal Treasurer exerts more effort to collect delinquent real property taxes. Avail of all collection remedies applicable in the current circumstance of the Municipality;
The OIC- Municipal Treasurer to coordinate/make representations with the Punong Barangays and seek their assistance to personally deliver the above notices/letters to concerned individuals in the locality and advise them to settle their accounts;
The Municipality make representation to the Provincial Government to consider administrative and judicial remedies in the collection of delinquent real property taxes as authorized by the Local Government Code. Coordinate with other local treasurers and adopt their procedures and best practices; and
The management to seek advice from the concerned government agencies regarding applicable remedies on the CARP covered properties.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to request a copy of the missing bank statements from the authorized bank in order to itemize the reconciling item in the amount of ₱0.692 million to determine their nature and make necessary adjusting entries, if necessary;
Advice the OIC - Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant in the adjustment of the identified reconciling items and provide the latter the needed data especially on the stale checks returned by the payees; and
Instruct the offices concerned to communicate to all the payees with long outstanding checks regarding the status of the checks issued and immediately take necessary action after the payee has returned the stale check to the Municipality.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive;
Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical inventory of the Municipality’s properties and prepare and submit the corresponding inventory report;
Require the GSO and the Municipal Accountant to maintain duly accomplished and updated property cards and ledger cards, respectively;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to provide depreciation to all properties after the conduct of inventory and submission of inventory report so that necessary adjusting entries be made;
Oblige the Inventory Committee to prepare report on the land owned by the Municipality and require the Municipal Assessor to register all real estate owned by the Municipality and create an Appraisal Committee to conduct assessment of the value of donated land to facilitate recording in the books of account of the Municipality; and
Require the GSO to submit the report on the public auction conducted to the Municipal Accountant so that the disposed unserviceable properties will be drop in the books.

We recommended the following:
The OIC- Municipal Treasurer exerts more effort to collect delinquent real property taxes. Avail of all collection remedies applicable in the current circumstance of the Municipality;
The OIC- Municipal Treasurer to coordinate/make representations with the Punong Barangays and seek their assistance to personally deliver the above notices/letters to concerned individuals in the locality and advise them to settle their accounts;
The Municipality make representation to the Provincial Government to consider administrative and judicial remedies in the collection of delinquent real property taxes as authorized by the Local Government Code. Coordinate with other local treasurers and adopt their procedures and best practices; and
The management to seek advice from the concerned government agencies regarding applicable remedies on the CARP covered properties.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to deposit all collections intact with the authorized depository bank daily or not later than the next banking day as required under existing laws, rules and regulations;
Instruct the OIC-Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to conduct regular reconciliation of the cash book and subsidiary ledger balances to ensure completeness and accuracy of the recorded transactions and the balance of Cash in Local Treasury account as of a given period;
Demand immediate deposit of the remaining undeposited amounts; and
Avail of possible legal remedies in regard to the accountability of the absconded Municipal Treasurer.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to request a copy of the missing bank statements from the authorized bank in order to itemize the reconciling item in the amount of ₱692,320.15;
Advice the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant in the adjustment of the identified reconciling items and provide the latter the needed data especially on the stale checks returned by the payee; and
Instruct the offices concerned to communicate to all the payees with long outstanding checks regarding the status of the checks issued and immediately take necessary action after the payee has returned the stale check to the Municipality.

We recommended that the Management:
Direct all the concerned officials/employees to immediately settle the outstanding cash advances, and all advances must be liquidated at year-end;
Establish a strong internal control and create a policy or standard operating procedures in the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advance which provides for the sanctions/penalties for non-compliance thereon subject to existing relevant laws, rules and regulations;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to refrain from granting additional cash advances unless the previous advance is liquidated, and coordinate with the management of other government agencies to direct the officials/employees previously assigned in the Municipality to immediately settle their outstanding accounts; and
Conduct regular and periodic verification, analysis and validation of the cash advances, determine long outstanding and dormant receivable accounts and prepare necessary reports together with the supporting documents for the request for write-off, if warranted, as indicated in COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We recommended the following:
The management to strictly enforce the collection of water fees from delinquent consumers by implementing the provisions of Municipal Ordinance No. 36-08 especially on the collection policy and the penal provisions stated therein;
The offices concerned to coordinate properly for proper recording of actual financial status and data particularly on the recognition of income and receivables in the books in order to assist the management in better decision-making;
The management to instruct the office of the waterworks to consistently inspect/check the water meters and water lines and prepare the report every month in order for the management to regularly conduct repair and maintenance; and
The management to enforce corrective measures and strictly impose sanctions, if warranted, in order to promote efficiency, economy and effectiveness in its operations.

We recommended that the Management:
Implement the provisions of RA No. 9003 especially on the establishment of a sanitary landfill or any other acceptable/authorized alternative types of dumpsite;
Implement the existing Municipal Ordinance regarding the solid waste management system by adopting measures to observe the basic environmental regulations and effective application of the Municipality’s solid waste management programs, projects and activities, as planned, to totally achieve the objective of RA No. 9003 in protecting the environment and public health;
Collaborate Information/Education/Communication (IEC) campaigns with barangay officials to achieve proper coordination and synchronization, and  establish focal persons in each barangay who shall be responsible in the arrangements and schedules of IEC campaigns;
Appropriate funds for the establishment of Materials Recovery Facilities (MRFs). Consequently, MRFs will be established in every barangay or cluster of barangays in the Municipality.  The Municipality may pilot a single barangay to establish the MRF project in order to institute a system of knowledge in establishing one as well as to gain commitment and participation of barangay officials on the proper administration and operation of MRFs; and
Strictly implement the policy on the use of personal protective equipment by the garbage collectors. An information campaign should be conducted to instill awareness in them.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the concerned officials to:
Initiate the creation and maintenance of a GAD Database containing sex-disaggregated data that will serve as basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation;
Formulate GAD Codes or Ordinances that will support the LGU’s efforts in promoting, protecting and fulfilling women’s human rights, women’s economic empowerment and gender-responsive governance towards the attainment of gender equality and women’s empowerment;
Prepare the GAD AR in accordance with the procedures and format provided in JMC No. 2013-01 and supported with necessary documents;
Conduct gender analysis and assessment in identifying gender issues and appropriate PPAs; and
Strictly adhere to the provisions of JMC No. 2013-01 of the PCW, DILG, DBM and NEDA.

10.1 We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the inventory Committee to conduct the physical inventory of PPE annually to prove their existence, determine the condition and update the valuation thru the following procedures:

Physically count all existing PPE and provide its description.  Secure other information such as person accountable/user, date of purchase, brand, model, serial no., engine no., etc. and determine if unserviceable or not;

Based on the information gathered in procedure no. 1, determine if there are accounting records for these PPEs.  Prepare a PPELC for each PPE with accounting records or data, identify and determine its total cost and compute a separate depreciation schedule. PPE without accounting records should be properly disclosed;

Identify the accountable employee for each PPE and issue a Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR);

We recommended that management correct the inefficiencies of the water system operations by ensuring that:

25.1Segregation of incompatible duties as meter reading, computation, billing, collection and recording are observed;
25.2 Water meters are regularly monitored so that defective and lost meters are promptly acted upon;

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Inventory Committee to conduct the physical inventory of PPE annually to prove its existence, determine the condition and update the valuation thru the following procedures:
Physically count all existing PPE and provide its description.  Secure other information such as person accountable/user, date of purchase, brand, model, serial no., engine no., etc. and determine if unserviceable or not;
Based on the information gathered in procedure no. 1 determine if there are accounting records for these PPEs.  Prepare a PPELC for each PPE with accounting records or data, identify and determine its total cost and compute a separate depreciation schedule. PPE without accounting records should be properly disclosed;
Identify the accountable employee for each PPE and issue a Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR)/Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE);
For the current purchases of PPE, immediately prepare a PPELC and issue a PAR/ARE to the employee;
Identify the employee responsible for the PPEs which no longer exist/or not presented and require the submission of an explanation and/or request for relief, if warranted; and
The Municipal Accountant shall make necessary adjusting entries to remove from the books PPEs which are unserviceable and were properly disposed.
We also recommended that the RPCPPE shall be submitted as required by regulations.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant shall;
Reconcile the correct balance of the Loans Payable with the bank, determine the cause of the difference and make necessary adjusting entries thereon; and
Present the balance of Loans Payable in the Financial Statements as “Current Liabilities” and “Non-current Liabilities”.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Accountant and other responsible municipal officials/employees to do the following:
Send demand letters to all accountable officers and withhold the unliquidated cash advances from the salaries of officials/employees who are still active in the service, if no actions were taken despite of the demand;
Require explanation from the active employees for non-settlement or non-liquidation of cash advances beyond the prescribed period;
Ensure that no clearance shall be issued to an employee with outstanding cash advances or require settlement of such prior to his/her separation from the service;
Devise a systematic monitoring of the account to avoid granting of additional cash advances to officers/employees with outstanding balances; and
Strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 and Section 89 of PD No. 1445.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive shall:
Direct the creation of a Solid Waste Management Board and prioritize the preparation of the 10-Year Solid Waste Management Plan and have it approved by the National Solid Waste Management Commission to ensure that the required efficient solid waste management is met;
Implement the provisions of RA No. 9003 especially on the establishment of sanitary landfill or any other acceptable/authorized alternative types of dumpsite; and
Implement the existing Municipal Ordinance regarding the solid waste management system by applying the following;
Impose a thorough collection of garbage based on set schedules for all barangays of the Municipality;
Replace the old dumptruck and acquire additional vehicle exclusively for garbage collection;
Require the strict implementation of waste segregation;
Organize Information, Education and Communication (IEC) campaign on proper waste segregation and disposal to the community;
Issue protective equipment to the garbage collector; and
Install other efficient and effective ways necessary to address the problem on garbage collection, segregation and disposal of the Municipality.
